The combat involves a deck building mechanic that is really robust, and IMPORTANT. The fairytale whimsy of Lost In Random doesn’t mean that this game is ‘easy.’ These enemies mean business, I found that out the hard way… several times.

There are obvious comparisons to The Nightmare Before Christmas to be made in this game, but it stands firmly on its own two feet thanks to some immediate world building in the opening act. The game wastes no time drawing you in, and introducing you to our heroes Even and Dicey.

A one will leave in the slums of Onecroft, but a six will have you sent to work in the Queen’s Palace in Sixtopia. Speaking of which, the Queen is a gay icon as far as I am concerned and I am happy to take questions on that.

Thank you to @EA and EA Game Changers for inviting me to immerse myself in a game that feels so unique yet familiar. The premise is wonderfully… feudal? On their twelfth birthday every citizen rolls a magic die that determines your fate!
